  "response_text": "The average reserve biomass across all patches begins at 90,000.00 at time step zero. During the initial phase, the metric exhibits a downward trend, reaching a minimum value of 84,114.07 at time step 26. This decline indicates an initial period of resource pressure before stabilization. Following this trough, the trajectory shifts to a sustained increase starting around time step 33. This upward trend continues significantly through the remainder of the simulation horizon. By time step 100, the average reserve biomass attains its maximum value of 121,072.59. A change point at time step 50 further characterizes the consolidation of this recovery phase. The final biomass level represents a substantial increase relative to the starting condition. Within the context of the model, where households employ diverse behavioral strategies including learning-by-doing and social learning without enforced pasture resting, this pattern suggests that agent adaptation mechanisms eventually align livestock pressure with regeneration rates. For decision makers, these dynamics imply that while early-stage resource depletion occurs, the inclusion of adaptive behavioral types supports long-term ecological resilience and resource recovery, indicating that monitoring and support during the initial twenty to thirty time steps are critical to prevent irreversible damage before learning processes yield positive outcomes."
}

